[3] Pakistan (Punjab)
Date: Mon 17 Jun 2013
Source: The Nation [edited]
http://www.nation.com.pk/pakistan-news-newspaper-daily-english-online/national/17-Jun-2013/another-105-measles-cases-reported


More and more measles patients continued to approach public sector hospitals in the [Punjab] province for treatment, enhancing the burden on already overloaded health facilities facing severe shortage of necessary drugs. On Sunday [16 Jun 2013], as many as 99 measles patients were admitted to different hospitals in the province, including 18 in Lahore. So far, 17 948 measles cases have been reported from across the province, including 5204 in Lahore.

The disease that broke out in Punjab virtually assumed shape of an epidemic as 6 to 10 measles-affected children were being reportedly taken on a daily basis [to] the 3 teaching hospitals from different parts of the district. Ironically, officials of the district health department termed the situation normal and under control, while the surge in cases of measles speaks otherwise.

HFH [Holy Family Hospital] Spokesman Dr Javed Hayat confirmed that a total of 6 children have been admitted in the hospital. He said that out of 6 children, 5 were brought from different areas of Rawalpindi and Islamabad while one [was brought] from Attock. He said that the doctors were medicating the patients and [that the] condition of all patients was stable.

So far, a total of 516 cases of measles have been reported in teaching hospitals including Benazir Bhutto Hospital, HFH and District Headquarters Hospital. Of the total number, 295 were only reported in HFH.

