[4] Canada (Ontario)
Date: Tue 18 Jun 2013
Source: Inside Halton, The Burington Post report [edited]
http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/3843649-three-measles-cases-in-burlington/


The Halton Region Health Department says 3 related cases of measles have been confirmed in Burlington [Ontario province]. People who visited any of the following locations on Saturday [8 Jun 2013] may have been exposed to measles:

- SportChek in Burlington Mall, Guelph Line and Fairview Street, at 1 p.m. until approximately 4 p.m.
- The Collector's Vault, near New Street and Guelph Line, between 10 a.m. and 1 p.m.
- Al's Source for Sports, 3485 Fairview St., between 1 and 4 p.m.

"Persons who have measles need to isolate themselves while they are ill and for 4 full days after the rash 1st appears," Halton Region Medical Officer of Health Dr. Bob Nosal said in a press release. Dr. Monir Taha, associate medical officer of health for Halton Region, told the Post all 3 of the cases involve children in the same family who are all under the age of 16. "To my knowledge nothing serious has happened to these children," said Taha. He noted they would all be past the contagious phase of the disease by now.

"We received notification of these cases at the end of the day on Friday [14 Jun 2013]. There were other locations, which included healthcare settings and sports events where exposure may have occurred. The health department has made good progress in contacting people. We continue to try connecting with people we don't get to right away," said Taha. "Our (measles) vaccination rate (in Halton) is 90 per cent but it's too bad it isn't even higher; it's highly infectious. You can never really have high enough immunity levels. Things (diseases) in the world are never more than an airport away."

Taha says reasons for those who have not been vaccinated can include an allergy to the vaccine, religious beliefs, lack of faith in its effectiveness or those with a weakened immune system being treated for cancer. Measles starts with a cough, a runny nose, red, watery eyes and a fever. After about 4 days a rash begins on the face and moves down the body. There may be white spots inside the mouth. Measles spreads easily to people who are not immune. Anyone born in 1970 or later that has not had 2 doses of measles vaccine is considered susceptible to the disease. Infants under one year old, pregnant women and those with weakened immune systems can get very ill with measles. Complications of measles can include middle ear infections, pneumonia, croup and inflammation of the brain. About one in 1000 people with measles die of it.

[Byline: Tim Whitnell]

